847. Laridum atque epulas is an extravagant combination. But it is not out of keeping with the style of Ergasilus' remarks throughout this Scene. Schoell reads ac (better atque, to be pronounced ae) pernas. The two words pernas and (e)pulas would be liable to confusion when written in minuscule contracted form. Foculis. The Neut. Plural fecula (from foveo, to warm3 cf. fomentum, fomes) is explained by Nonius, p. 10 Μ.; ‘Focula’ dieta sunt nutrimenta; unde et ‘foculare' dicitur, ut fovere, with quotation of Plaut. Pers. 104: At ecles; nam iam intus uentris fumant focula. (By nutrimenta he seems to mean nutrimenta iynis.)

848. Praestinatum. Paul. F est. 280. 4 Th.: ‘Praestz‘nare' apud Plautum praeemere est, z'd est emendo tenere. The word is rare, and is apparently brought into requisition in this line for the sake of the allitera- tion. Similarly Pseud. 169 Eyo eo in macellum, ut piscium quidquid ibist pretio praestinem. In Epz'd. 277, the only other instance of the word in Plautus, the Compound with the Preposition prae is required by the sense: U t enim praestines arqento, prius quam ueniat filius. Of. destinare. Vigilans somniat, “‘is dreaming while he is awake,’ i.e. is talking nonsense3 Amph. 697; cf. astans somniat, Men. 395. This should be dis- tinguished from uiyilans dormit, ‘is sleeping while he seems to be awake,' i.e. is stupid, Pseud. 386. Cf. vigilans stertis Lucr. iii. 1048.'' Morris.
